# Source: availability-heuristics-in-qa (3 ideas → 2 questions, 1 skipped)
{"question": "is it bad that our testers keep testing the same areas where they found bugs before?", "ground_truth": "Not necessarily. Availability heuristic — a cognitive shortcut where people assess likelihood based on how easily examples come to mind (Tversky and Kahneman) — can be a positive force in QA. Testers who notice patterns from past experience can preemptively design tests to catch bugs before production. However, it becomes harmful when it distorts prioritization, e.g., prioritizing i18n testing over urgent core features because of a memorable personal experience."}
{"question": "how do cognitive biases affect test prioritization?", "ground_truth": "The availability heuristic can distort test prioritization — testers may prioritize areas where they personally experienced memorable bugs rather than areas with the highest actual risk. For example, prioritizing i18n testing over urgent core features because of a memorable personal experience."}
