{"question": "what are REST's core design principles?", "ground_truth": "REST follows six principles: statelessness, cacheability, layered system architecture, uniform interface, client-server decoupling, and code on demand. SOAP offers protocol independence (HTTP, SMTP, TCP, JMS) and WS-Security but with XML verbosity overhead."}
# Source: sanity-testing (4 ideas → 2 questions, 2 skipped)
{"question": "what's the difference between smoke testing and sanity testing?", "ground_truth": "Sanity testing checks one or more specific parts of the application after modifications, while smoke testing checks critical functionality with broader coverage. Sanity testing is a subset of regression testing and occurs after smoke testing."}
{"question": "how do we do sanity testing?", "ground_truth": "Sanity testing follows three stages: identification (locate changes), evaluation (verify components operate per specifications), and testing (execute comprehensive testing on new components). It uses surface-level, often manual testing with focused scope."}
# Source: shift-left-testing (4 ideas → 2 questions, 2 skipped)
{"question": "what are the different ways to implement shift-left testing?", "ground_truth": "Shift-left testing has three types: traditional (unit/integration testing and early QA involvement), Agile/DevOps (testing embedded in CI/CD pipelines with automated testing on code commits), and incremental (gradual movement, less disruptive for organizations)."}
{"question": "how do we actually start shift-left testing?", "ground_truth": "Start with requirements testing for stakeholder alignment, then empower developers to write automated unit, API, and integration tests, advance through TDD, and implement mob programming for continuous feedback. Mob programming 'virtually eliminates' queues and late feedback issues."}
# Source: smoke-testing (4 ideas → 2 questions, 2 skipped)
{"question": "what is smoke testing and when should we do it?", "ground_truth": "Smoke testing assesses software stability and readiness for subsequent testing phases — also called build verification testing, build acceptance testing, or confidence testing. Passing indicates readiness for functional testing."}
{"question": "manual, automated, or hybrid smoke testing?", "ground_truth": "Three types: manual (manually created and updated test cases), automated (uses software tools, faster and reusable), and hybrid (combines manual test case writing with automation tools). Smoke testing follows five steps: choose type, create scenarios per core function, develop tests, execute and record, analyze results."}
