# Source: software-testing-types-approaches-levels-execution-strategies-and-techniques-the-complete-guide (5 ideas → 4 questions, 1 skipped)
{"question": "how do we build a test strategy from scratch?", "ground_truth": "Follow a risk-based framework: name the risk mapped to ISO 25010, select the lowest effective test level, pick design techniques with coverage targets, choose practices for delivery, balance static with dynamic execution, and set measurable acceptance targets (SLOs, WCAG, CVSS thresholds)."}
{"question": "what's the difference between test types, test levels, and test techniques?", "ground_truth": "Testing taxonomy separates type (what quality goal, mapped to ISO 25010), level (where in lifecycle), and technique/practice (how executed). Conflating these causes logical traps like 'performance testing only means end-to-end.' Software testing is an economic and risk-management activity."}
{"question": "what are the software testing levels and what does each catch?", "ground_truth": "Levels form a hierarchy: unit → component → component-integration/contract → system → system-integration → acceptance (UAT/OAT/FAT) → alpha/beta/field. Lower levels catch local logic errors, integration reveals interface mismatches, system exposes end-to-end behavior, acceptance validates user suitability."}
{"question": "is static testing worth the effort if we already have good automated tests?", "ground_truth": "Yes. Static testing (code reviews, SAST/linters, architecture reviews) enables action weeks earlier than dynamic testing since artifacts precede working product. Defects removed in reviews are far cheaper than those found after deployment."}
# Source: stress-testing-software (4 ideas → 2 questions, 2 skipped)
{"question": "stress testing vs load testing vs performance testing — what's the difference?", "ground_truth": "Stress testing checks system stability under extreme load conditions. Performance testing measures under typical conditions. Load testing evaluates under anticipated user load."}
{"question": "what types of stress testing are there?", "ground_truth": "Six types: distributed (all server clients), application (data locking, network issues), transaction (between multiple applications), system (multiple systems on one server), exploratory (unusual parameters), and spike (repeated large loads). Monitor three metric categories: scalability/performance, application response, and failure metrics."}
# Source: system-integration-testing-sit (4 ideas → 2 questions, 2 skipped)
{"question": "what is system integration testing and how is it different from other integration tests?", "ground_truth": "System integration testing (SIT) checks whether all tested modules work together as a whole once combined. It is the final integration testing phase before end-to-end tests. SIT focuses on functional integration, while system tests cover functional and nonfunctional testing, and UAT involves nonfunctional evaluation with user participation."}
{"question": "what approach should we use for system integration testing?", "ground_truth": "Three approaches: bottom-up (lowest to highest components), top-down (highest to lowest), and big-bang (all components tested simultaneously). Granularity is adjustable from component level to system-wide. SIT should be performed frequently and early, include regression testing, and prioritize legacy system compatibility."}
# Source: test-automation-as-investment-not-just-technical-choice (4 ideas → 3 questions, 1 skipped)
{"question": "how do we justify the cost of test automation to management?", "ground_truth": "Frame test automation as an economic decision with three types of value: reducing repetitive work (manual regression), improving release speed (faster feedback), and enabling new testing types (stress testing, security scans, chaos testing that humans cannot perform). Quantify ROI: if a bottleneck task takes 4 hours weekly across 5 engineers, that equals 20 engineer-hours saved monthly."}
{"question": "how should we roll out test automation?", "ground_truth": "Follow a five-step investment approach: define desired value type, select a small high-impact target, automate incrementally in small testable batches, measure actual value using real data, and scale only when ROI is proven. Avoid up-front comprehensive cost estimates — software effort estimations are notoriously unreliable."}
{"question": "should we estimate the full cost of test automation upfront?", "ground_truth": "No. Avoid up-front comprehensive cost estimates — software effort estimations are notoriously unreliable. Prefer incremental delivery with feedback loops and experimental pilots before full-scale rollout."}
# Source: test-driven-development (4 ideas → 3 questions, 1 skipped)
{"question": "how does TDD work step by step?", "ground_truth": "TDD follows the Red-Green-Refactor cycle: write one failing test (Red), write the simplest code to pass it (Green), then eliminate duplication and improve readability (Refactor) — repeat for each requirement. Governed by Robert C. Martin's three laws: no production code unless it makes a failing test pass, only write enough test code to fail, only write enough production code to pass the one failing test."}
{"question": "does TDD actually reduce bugs?", "ground_truth": "Yes. A Microsoft case study showed pre-release defect density decreased 40-90% versus non-TDD projects, though TDD adds 15-35% to initial implementation time. 92% of surveyed developers believe it yields higher quality code."}
{"question": "does TDD replace the need for other testing?", "ground_truth": "No. TDD does not replace performance, stress, or usability testing. Its effectiveness depends on individual developers' expertise."}
# Source: the-test-pyramid-and-its-discontents (4 ideas → 2 questions, 2 skipped)
{"question": "should we follow the test pyramid?", "ground_truth": "The test pyramid should not be used as a prescriptive model. It has no agreed definitions — 'unit' means different things to different people. Testing should be reality-driven based on actual code/product needs, measuring success by team confidence and code quality rather than pyramid adherence."}
{"question": "what are the alternatives to the test pyramid?", "ground_truth": "Variations include Fowler's model (Unit → Service → UI), Google's model (80/15/5 ratio for unit/integration/E2E), Kent C. Dodds' Testing Trophy (emphasizing integration), and Spotify's Testing Honeycomb (Implementation → Integration → Integrated). Using any model as a prescriptive target suffers from Goodhart's Law."}
