{"question": "what is total quality management and how does it apply to software?", "ground_truth": "Total quality management (TQM) is a management approach centered on continuous improvement with four core principles: customer focus, total employee involvement and communication, strategic and systemic approach, and continuous improvement (Kaizen). In software, TQM means transitioning from QC to QA, implementing shift-left testing, replacing code reviews with pair/mob programming, and using CI/CD to shorten PDCA cycles."}
{"question": "how do we implement total quality management customer focus in software?", "ground_truth": "Total quality management (TQM) customer focus includes dogfooding (using your own product), Voice of Customer practices (surveys, interviews, focus groups), and gathering feedback through CRM systems."}
{"question": "how expensive is poor software quality?", "ground_truth": "Poor software quality cost approximately $2.8 trillion in the US (2018). 70% of consumers switch brands for better product quality. Total quality management (TQM) addresses this through continuous improvement and employee involvement with top management buy-in."}
