{"question": "what types of user acceptance testing are there?", "ground_truth": "User acceptance testing (UAT) has five types: alpha & beta testing, black box testing, contract acceptance testing (against predetermined criteria), regulation acceptance testing (HIPAA, GDPR compliance), and operational acceptance testing (installation, load balancing, backup/recovery)."}
{"question": "what goes wrong with UAT?", "ground_truth": "Three major challenges: scope creep (emerging requirements derailing original scope), premature UAT (product pushed before prerequisites complete), and ambiguous criteria (vague acceptance standards instead of concrete requirements). 75% of companies run multiple UAT cycles, and 57% cite poor software quality as the reason for reruns."}
{"question": "how many rounds of UAT should we expect?", "ground_truth": "75% of companies run multiple UAT cycles, and 57% cite poor software quality as the reason for reruns. User acceptance testing occurs late in the development lifecycle after system integration and regression testing."}
# Source: verification-vs-validation (4 ideas → 2 questions, 2 skipped)
{"question": "what's the difference between verification and validation?", "ground_truth": "Verification answers 'are we building the product right?' — ongoing throughout development using static methods (inspections, walkthroughs, reviews). Validation answers 'are we building the right product?' — after development using dynamic methods (functional testing, system testing, UAT). Barry Boehm formulated this distinction."}
{"question": "do we need both verification and validation or is one enough?", "ground_truth": "Both are required for complete testing results. Verification enables early issue identification during development, while validation ensures product reliability and stakeholder satisfaction post-development."}
